metadata.name: the boxes we live in #420
metadata.description:
Throughout our lives we are placed in boxes that define who we are and limit how we think of ourselves. 

I am a father, husband, son, brother, friend. I am an artist, programmer, photographer, musician, designer, creator. I am a student and I am a teacher. I am a good person. I am a bad person. I am a human.

What boxes do you put yourself in, and do you let others put you in? Is it possible to break out of the boxes that define your life? Do you even want to? What's outside of these boundaries? What is at the center?

metadata.description:
Enjoying donuts and coffee with a friend after smoking some cannabis together is a high pleasure.  

If it has been a while since you‚Äôve done this, or if you are looking for a very good first-time or reboot ganja experience ‚Ä¶ find yourself a stoner friend and make this happen!  Donuts is a generative 3D algorithm that celebrates this very special stoners‚Äô moment.

metadata.name: Adherence #89
metadata.description:
https://www.bfos.art/projects/adherence

======~~~~~~~~~~===================
We aren‚Äôt all moving in the same direction.  Sometimes we strictly follow the paths we are destined for.  Sometimes we meander in our own way and on our own time.  Let‚Äôs explore the ways that these different paths can create beauty.
=================~~~~~~~===========


============Adherence?=============
The title feature of Adherence controls how obediently each of the streamers follow their curated path and whether they die off when destined. While each mint will have a default level of adherence, everyone will be able to see what their piece would look like at all other levels of obedience.

You might prefer to live life conservatively doing everything that is expected of you‚Ä¶but then you‚Äôll be surprised at what joy and beauty can come from a rebellious spirit.


============No Restraint============
This project is definitely not a lesson in artistic restraint. It has been very exciting for me to grow this project along with my learnings. I‚Äôve spent 6 months building, adding, cutting, and tweaking.  All of this wrestling has left an embarrassingly mangled code base.  That said, I truly believe the diversity of the output-space is worth it.  

During development, I encountered some very severe roadblocks, some of which I felt I might never be able to resolve. One in particular, related to ensuring this project is dimensionless, actually brought me to tears once I finally worked through it. Similarly, there were a fair number of major leaps that took just a few minutes from concept to implementation. 

My objective for my next project will be to bring more restraint‚Ä¶for the sake of my sanity if nothing else. It might take me just as long to complete and I expect that it will be a far smaller release, but I‚Äôll still put just as much care into making sure I deliver a quality project for anyone willing to mint.


============Open and Ugly============
I won‚Äôt be obscuring my code.  Anyone is free to use browser dev tools to look and learn to their heart‚Äôs content.

Be ye forewarned, though.  It‚Äôs not pretty.  I started out well enough, but little tweaks here and there to play and expand on the project has resulted in a code base I might be a little embarrassed about.

But, that‚Äôs OK!  We are all in this together and maybe this will be a way of helping others not feel intimidated by a sense of perfection.  I have also included fairly verbose comments, too, as added commentary to my insanity.

I hope that my openness and vulnerability will be seen by everyone in the community as an invitation to connect with me for any reason.  If you'd like to ask me any questions about this project, about my collecting, about learning to code, about working through challenges, or whatever else...please don't hesitate to ping me in just about any of the fx(hash) related discords (Kaloh's, TENDER, fx(hash), clewcrew) or on twitter.  


============Interactions============
{F}eatures
{P}rogress
{S}ave at current resolution
{N}oise Switch
{1-3} Adjust Adherence
{4-9} Save at x¬≤ resolution
{I}nfinite Animation Modes - [Experimental] 

There are two infinite animation modes.  I call them experimental because they didn't quite reach the level of polish that I would have preferred.  

The first mode is a loop-with-reverse.  It runs efficiently, but I think it's a little too obvious what it is doing.  It also messes with the background color.

The second mode is a more subtle loop that I actually love, but performance is VERY dependent on your device.  My M1 Mac runs it fairly well, but most other devices struggle through frames.  Even at a lower framerate, I think it's a neat effect.  Though, I wish I was able to figure out a way to improve the performance.  I tried a lot of tricks, but none helped that much.

======~~~~~~~~~~==============================~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~==============================

metadata.name: Mandelroid #95
metadata.description:
The Mandelbrot set is a mathematical object that is generated by a simple formula, and it exhibits some interesting visual patterns that are reminiscent of those found in nature, such as the self-similarity of branching structures, the repetition of small-scale patterns on larger scales, and the presence of chaotic behavior.

The beauty of Polaroid film lies in its ability to capture and preserve a moment in space and time in a unique and tangible way.

This work combines two things that are incongruent with each other and brings them together to create a digital memory that serves as a reminder that complexity can be found even in the simplest things, that art is intrinsic to nature itself.

‚Ä¢ press '1' to scale the photo to 1024x1024 pixels (the default output)
‚Ä¢ press '2' to scale the photo to 2048x2048 pixels (Warning: can be slow!)
‚Ä¢ press '3' to scale the photo to 4096x4096 pixels (Warning: can be very slow!)
‚Ä¢ press 'd' to save the Mandelbrot Set
‚Ä¢ press 's' to save the Polaroid film

Done with p5.js
Simone "OuterSilent" Ferrari | @outertales | December 2022

metadata.name: 365 Tentacles #20
metadata.description:
Wow, Fxhash ! What a year !

For #fxhashturnsone I decided to explore how far I could take a simple concept: drawing 365 tentacles.
This turned out to be an interesting exercise, as having a strict limitation seemed to spark more ideas than when having complete freedom. There's a lot you can do with 365 things !

99.9% of primary sales go to the Processing Foundation.

Key commands:
's' to save a png image
'1', '2', '4' to change resolution
'+', '-' to change rendering zoom
